Flux quantization on  orientifolds 


Flux quantization on orientifolds is quite subtle, since there exist
3-cycles "smaller" than the ones on the torus.
As defined above, the fluxes of  and  must belong to
, and respectively,
the homological Poincare duals  and  must belong to .
Fluxes for  orbifold 

Following the arguments used in , one notices that under the
 and the  action  a
toroidal 3-cycle , in a general position, is mapped to an
orbit of eight toroidal 3-cycles all wrapping the same homology
class on . Therefore, what is usually called a bulk 3-cycle
on the orientifold of  is actually, from the toroidal point of
view, a cycle where  all  and  
are multiplesBy that we actually mean  and 
, .  of 8. Hence the associated fluxes have
 quantized in 
multiples of 64.
Besides these bulk cycles totally inherited from
the ambient , there are so-called twisted 3-cycles, which
also wrap some of the 48 3-cycles hidden in the various 
fixed points. Note that since the twisted cycles are "shorter"
than the toroidal ones, the corresponding fluxes can carry smaller
quanta of . 
This is important for model-buliding since, as we will see later, the bulk
flux contribution, which is a quantum of , always exceeds the
negative contribution of the O3-planes to the R-R tadpole 
cancellation condition.



Hence supersymmetric configurations can only be obtained by switching on
some  twisted
fluxes (with ).

Fluxes for  orbifold 

For the model with
discrete torsion the situation is a bit more subtle.
In the following, we will argue that here  and
 are only quantized in units of 4. Again arguing
about the homology, ,  we consider first
3-cycles on the  orbifold space, i.e.
neglecting the orientifold projection for the moment. Naively, one
obtains that under the action  of  a
bulk 3-cycle on the orbifold corresponds to an orbit of four toroidal
3-cycles, . One can show that the intersection numbers for
these  bulk cycles are multiples of 4. Since the twisted sectors
do not contain any additional 3-cycles, there must exist smaller
toroidal 3-cycles, as  an integral basis of 
yields  a unimodular intersection form. Thus, we conclude that there
must exist 3-cycles in the orbifold, which correspond to only
toroidal orbits of length two: .

These shorter 3-cycles can be seen as follows.
Consider the -twisted sector. In this sector, besides
the bulk 3-cycles,
we can define  fractional 3-cycles, which are of the form
,
where  denotes a toroidal cycle and  a 3-cycle
in the -twisted sector.
Under the action of the second 
such a fractional cycle is mapped to , so that the
whole orbit under  gives rise to a pure
toroidal  cycle , which is indeed what we are looking for.


Taking also the  action into account, we
conclude  that in the 
orientifold model with discrete torsion, the coefficients
in the expansion
 1(2)^2[G]=
e_  A^ + m^  B_   
are multiples of 4.


Therefore here the  is quantized
in multiples of 16, which does not exceed the contribution
from the O3-planes.




